#. type: Content of: <book><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:7
#, no-wrap
msgid "the Complete Gentoo/Linux handbook"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:14
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This handbook tries to extend on various subjects regarding Linux and the Gentoo\n"
"Linux operating system. It is written with the casual user in mind who wants to\n"
"learn about Linux rather than just follow instructions to the letter. Although I\n"
"hope this handbook will eventually be complete, it currently lacks so many\n"
"important subjects that it is far from ready yet to be officially published.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction to Linux"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:31
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Linux is a great concept. It is a wonderful kernel and has wonderful userland\n"
"utilities making it a perfect operating system. But for most people, it is quite\n"
"new and too exciting to just dive in. This part tries to cover Linux: what is\n"
"it, how does it work, what can you expect etc.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "What is Linux?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:40
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"What is Linux exactly? How does this all fit in \"Free Software\"? What is a\n"
"distribution and why would you care? How is Linux developed? What can you expect\n"
"from it? All that is covered in this chapter.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "Users and the Linux file system"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:50
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Linux is built upon the UNIX knowledge and concepts. This means it is fairly\n"
"robust and uses a very logical approach to files, users and such. But for most\n"
"people, this logical approach is just what seems the most illogical since they\n"
"are not used to it. In this chapter, we try to inform those users about how\n"
"Linux sees a multi-user environment and what the Linux file system is structured\n"
"like.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "Freedom, support and finances"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:63
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The most powerful asset of the Linux operating system is the freedom it gives\n"
"you. But many folks are afraid that this freedom comes with a price: no support,\n"
"no company backing up Linux. This is all FUD (Fear, Uncertainty, Doubt) and well\n"
"explained in this chapter.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "Staying up to date"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:74
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With the decentralised development model that Linux uses, keeping a system up to\n"
"date might seem like a huge effort. Indeed, it is, but it is covered by the\n"
"various distributions (such as Gentoo). However, because of the openness that\n"
"the development model imposes, users have conflicting feelings about stability\n"
"and the differences between all version models. This chapter explains what all\n"
"the differences between version models are.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:85
#, no-wrap
msgid "Making a choice"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:87
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that most non-technical stuff is covered, it is time for you to make\n"
"choices. Will you use Linux? What distribution? What graphical environment? What\n"
"mail client? In this chapter we discuss the various differences between\n"
"major distributions and explain that, once you have picked a distribution, all\n"
"other choices are reversible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:97
#, no-wrap
msgid "Finding information"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:99
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You have a lot of resources at your disposal, but you need to know where to look\n"
"for them. In this chapter we provide you a quick overview on the available\n"
"resources, how to use them for your queries and what you can do to contribute to\n"
"them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "So far so good"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:110
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that the introduction to Linux has ended, we will talk about the next few\n"
"parts and the syntax we use throughout this document.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:118
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing Gentoo"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:120
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So you decided to install Gentoo. That's great, so how to continue? Installing\n"
"Gentoo is a breeze, but not a soft one. You need to have a fair knowledge of the\n"
"Linux environment if you want to get it right from the first time. In this part,\n"
"we discuss how to install Gentoo using the available Gentoo media. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:127
#, no-wrap
msgid "Versions, media and installation concerns"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Gentoo provides installation media, with specific versions, for specific\n"
"architectures, for specific installation methods. This chapter informs you how\n"
"to pick the right media for your system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "Starting from a minimal environment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:139
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The start of every Gentoo installation process begins with a minimal Linux\n"
"environment, allowing you to extract a basic Gentoo environment on your disk.\n"
"Regardless of what minimal environment you are in, you need to know a few basic\n"
"things about the system. This chapter covers the use of important tools.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:148
#, no-wrap
msgid "Preparing the network"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:150
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When you are known to the minimal environment, it is time to get the network up\n"
"and running. We will inform you how a network is set up, what TCP/IP is and how\n"
"to deal with networking on Linux, including wireless networks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:158
#, no-wrap
msgid "Putting the minimal environment in place"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:160
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this chapter we prepare your disk(s) to store the Gentoo Linux environment.\n"
"We will cover a few additional storage concepts (LVM2, RAID) but the real use of\n"
"these technologies is postponed for later. Next, we store a minimal Gentoo\n"
"environment on your disks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:169
#, no-wrap
msgid "Building the system"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:171
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once the minimal environment was available, we took the dive and chrooted in it.\n"
"Now, we'll set up the basic configuration directives, build the Gentoo\n"
"system until it is bootstrapped and has the core system packages available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:179
#, no-wrap
msgid "Building the Linux kernel"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:181
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The core of any Linux Operating System is the kernel. Configuring a kernel might\n"
"seem like a difficult task, but once you get to know how it works, it hardly is\n"
"a challenge anymore. In this chapter we will discuss how to configure and build\n"
"your kernel, either automatically using genkernel, or manually with the kernel\n"
"configuration dialog.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:191
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring the boot process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:193
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The next step is to configure the boot process. The boot process covers the boot\n"
"loader tool, which loads the Linux kernel in memory, and the init process which\n"
"governs all the applications and processes that should start on a Linux system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:202
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring the system"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:204
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Most of the system's configuration is stored inside /etc. In this almost final\n"
"chapter we describe what you should configure prior to rebooting (such as the \n"
"file system table, networking stuff, user accounts, ...). It is important to \n"
"read this entire chapter completely.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:213
#, no-wrap
msgid "Finishing off"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:215
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that everything is (hopefully) configured correctly, we reboot in the Gentoo\n"
"Linux Operating System to discover that we have a nice running minimal\n"
"environment. Now, where to go from here? You obviously can't work immediately\n"
"since nothing is installed yet...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:225
#, no-wrap
msgid "Gentoo Linux for the desktop user"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:227
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Most Gentoo users have a Gentoo-powered desktop system, yet are often unaware of\n"
"the massive tools and helpful features that Linux offers to increase their\n"
"desktop experience. In this part you'll find pointers to various tips and\n"
"tricks, but also best practices for desktop users.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:234
#, no-wrap
msgid "Graphical Linux"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:236
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Linux is not an operating system where command-line utilities must be used. Once\n"
"the system is installed, any user should be able to use it without any knowledge\n"
"of command-line utilities. Indeed, this is perfectly possible, but requires some\n"
"configuration. This chapter gives an introduction to popular graphical\n"
"environments and provides pointers to its configuration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:246
#, no-wrap
msgid "Plug and play"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:248
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Your laptop detects an open wireless network and authenticates itself\n"
"immediately. You plug in your USB key which gets mounted immediately so you can\n"
"download the latest Gentoo release on it. While you are at it, your calendar\n"
"synchronises with your friends while your laptop tries to consume as little\n"
"power as possible because it is working on batteries. No, this is no utopia...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:258
#, no-wrap
msgid "Software collaboration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:260
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Open standards allow for easy integration of different software tools. However,\n"
"the race for the best open standard hasn't been won, so various tools only work\n"
"with one standard while other tools use a different one. This chapter gives a \n"
"quick overview of the various collaboration-related standards and the \n"
"applications (or libraries which they use) that make use of them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:272
#, no-wrap
msgid "Gentoo Linux for enterprise environments"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:274
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Enterprises require more than just a stable Operating System. Depending on their\n"
"requirements, a system should be high-available, have a high throughput, connect\n"
"with legacy systems, have a low maintenance cost, requires zero manual\n"
"configuration steps, etc. This part will attempt to discuss various interesting\n"
"topics that might help you get more out of Gentoo Linux.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:282
#, no-wrap
msgid "Software RAID"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:284
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you need a very low-cost system but still want redundancy, using software\n"
"RAID is a minimal requirement. In this chapter we will describe how to use\n"
"software RAID within Gentoo Linux.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:292
#, no-wrap
msgid "Logical Volume Management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:294
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With LVM, storage concerns can be tackled easily since your files are located on\n"
"top of a specific layer, able to hide the complexity of storage from the file\n"
"system. Learn how to store files across various file systems, moving data\n"
"without the need to put the system in a frozen state, take live backups without\n"
"having your data touched while you are busy, ... and all that using LVM2.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:304
#, no-wrap
msgid "Backup systems"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:306
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You don't want to lose your files, but eventually you will. Having backups at\n"
"hand is a prerequisite for good system householding, but is also often\n"
"overlooked or deemed less important. This chapter will cover a few basics on\n"
"backups and proposes a few solutions that will help you keep your data safe.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:315
#, no-wrap
msgid "Print server"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:317
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"High quality printing is a requirement for every office. Linux makes a fine\n"
"print server, capable of interacting with all possible applications and\n"
"operating systems.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:327
#, no-wrap
msgid "System Administration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:329
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once your system is set up, your next concern is to decide how to administer the\n"
"system. Some people have made system administration their full-time job. We'll\n"
"try to keep the administration to a minimum without losing flexibility.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:335
#, no-wrap
msgid "Software management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:337
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Gentoo's Portage is a powerful software management tool with lots of features.\n"
"Not only can you easily install and remove software, rebuild tools when they are\n"
"affected by changes or update your system entirely, it also supports prebuilt\n"
"packages and different repositories.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:346
#, no-wrap
msgid "Log files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:348
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Not many resources talk about log files. Most documents assume that log files\n"
"are mentioned by the application documentation, yet many applications just\n"
"inform you what information you can find in the logs and that isn't sufficient\n"
"for a good log management policy. Log rotation, event filtering, summary\n"
"creation, ... are all aspects that this chapter covers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:358
#, no-wrap
msgid "Centralised system management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:360
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When you administer more than one system, it might be beneficial to set up and\n"
"maintain your environment from a single location. You can use SSH to log on to\n"
"other systems, but more advanced tools exist that offer a wide variety of\n"
"features.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:371
#, no-wrap
msgid "Performance tuning"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:373
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"No system is equal, so many systems have one or more performance bottlenecks due\n"
"to general settings that aren't as optimal for their systems as they are for\n"
"others. You can increase your systems performance on many areas as long as you\n"
"understand why they are bottlenecks and what sacrifices you need to make to\n"
"increase the throughput.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:381
#, no-wrap
msgid "Input/output performance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:383
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Storage performance. If there is one device in your system that has the highest\n"
"importance but one of the lowest access times, it is your storage. Disks aren't\n"
"fast, network storage isn't much better and memory disks are generally too small\n"
"to contain your entire system. So what can you do to increase the IO\n"
"performance?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:393
#, no-wrap
msgid "Network performance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:395
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you are on a 28.8 kbps network, you'll always find that it is slow. Many\n"
"people still think their network is slow while they're using a 1 Gbps network.\n"
"By identifying the bottlenecks in your network and designing a good topology,\n"
"you can increase the performance of your network to a good level.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:404
#, no-wrap
msgid "Rendering performance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:406
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A gamers wet dream: screens and graphical cards that render 3D images so\n"
"detailed and so fast that it seems that you're looking through a window. Of\n"
"course, this isn't achievable yet, but it is possible to tune the 3D performance\n"
"of your card. Of course, we'll take a look at 2D rendering as well.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:415
#, no-wrap
msgid "Software profiling"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:417
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Programmers don't always write the most performant code; perhaps because they\n"
"rely on the compiler to enhance the machine code or because they want to write\n"
"clean and maintainable code, setting their priorities elsewhere. Using profiling\n"
"tools, you can find out where in the software the performance bottlenecks may\n"
"lie.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:427
#, no-wrap
msgid "User-observed performance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:429
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Lately, developers have come to the conclusion that even the fastest solution\n"
"can lose against a less performant system - at least if a human being is to\n"
"observe and judge. Many interesting projects have emerged where design\n"
"patterns and guidelines are discussed that try to embrace the users thoughts on\n"
"speed and performance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:442
#, no-wrap
msgid "Appendix: architecture specific information"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:444
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Not all aspects of a Gentoo Linux system are similar on all architectures. Some\n"
"small differences come up during and after the installation. This part will\n"
"cover all architecture-specific information, nicely divided in separate chapters\n"
"for each architecture.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:451
#, no-wrap
msgid "The x86 Architecture"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <book><part><chapter><abstract>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/handbook.xml:453
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The x86 architecture covers all 32-bit Intel and Intel-clones, such as the \n"
"various AMD processors (the K-series and Athlon/Duron), VIA and Cyrix. The CPU\n"
"types range from the old (but functional) i386 to the latest Intel Pentium IV\n"
"and AMD Athlons.\n"
msgstr ""
